  {
    "page": 1,
    "block_id": "page_001:block_052",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "Modern software systems increasingly rely on third-party open-source components, which now constitute the majority of code in typical applications. While this reuse accelerates development, it also exposes systems to significant security risks, as known vulnerabilities in reused components can propagate downstream. To assess such risks, maintainers and Software Composition Analysis (SCA) tools depend on public vulnerability databases, such as the National Vulnerability Database (NVD) and GitHub Advisories, which specify affected version ranges. However, recent studies have shown that these databases often contain inaccurate or incomplete version metadata, leading to false negatives that leave systems unpatched or false positives that trigger unnecessary and potentially disruptive upgrades. This issue is amplified by the rapid growth in reported vulnerabilities and the adoption of large language models (LLMs), which accelerate vulnerability detection but shift pressure to the slower downstream tasks of confirmation and auditing. In this paper, we propose CaVulner , an automated, LLM-assisted framework for context-aware identification of vulnerable versions. To localize vulnerable code, CaVulner first narrows candidate methods using commit change patterns and CVE/CWE metadata, then guides the LLM to extract the root cause through fine-grained reasoning over pre- and post-fix code. To infer affected versions, CaVulner traces vulnerability-inducing commits using git blame, identifies semantically duplicated commits via hunk hash comparison, and normalizes their associated tags into standardized version ranges. We evaluated CaVulner on 43 real-world Java open source projects that included 176 CVEs and 8,730 versions. The results show that CaVulner significantly outperforms state - of - the - art approaches, including V - SZZ, VERJava, and LLM4SZZ. It achieves an accuracy gain of at least 35.8% on CVE level. At the version level, F1 - score increases by at least 23.94%, and the cost of using the LLM per vulnerability is only around $0.06. It offers a scalable and semantically grounded solution for supply chain security.",
    "bbox": [
      45.604000091552734,
      139.60279846191406,
      440.4047546386719,
      371.17236328125
    ],
    "reading_order": 52,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
