    "text": "Modern software development heavily relies on third-party open-source software (OSS). The World Economic Forum highlights that OSS makes up as much as 70% to 90% of the code in software systems [ 10 ]. While the reuse of OSS significantly improves development efficiency and reduces costs, it also introduces substantial security risks. For instance, a report [ 6 ] by Black Duck reveals that 86% of codebases contain components with known vulnerabilities. The number of known software vulnerabilities has been increasing rapidly in recent years, which extensively influenced the ecosystem. To manage this growing threat, organizations such as the National Vulnerability Database (NVD) [ 31 ] and GitHub Advisory Database [ 2 ] curate critical information on disclosed vulnerabilities, to support the wide usage of software supply chain tools like Software Composition Analysis (SCA), to assess potential risks. In this case, SCA tools rely heavily on the accuracy of vulnerability data, especially the correct vulnerable versions, for automated mappings of security risks in downstream user projects. However, multiple studies [ 9 , 16 , 33 , 42 ] have shown that these vulnerability records often contain inconsistencies or errors, which can seriously mislead maintenance decisions. Moreover, as the integration of large language models (LLMs) has significantly accelerated the discovery of new vulnerabilities, the downstream tasks, like vulnerability confirmation and auditing, face increasing pressure to keep pace, and more automated solutions with less human effort, especially on vulnerable version identification, are urgently needed. To precisely identify vulnerable versions in OSS, researchers have proposed a variety of solutions broadly categorized into dynamic analysis and static analysis. Dynamic approaches [ 26 , 45 , 47 , 48 ] typically employ fuzzing to confirm whether a vulnerability can be triggered. While dynamic meth- ods produce no false positives, they inherently suffer from false negatives due to the fundamental",
